In this project we will try to solve the given maze by AI search algorithms: BFS, IDS and A* first we read the input inyo a 2D list then we run each algorithm for 3 given tests

Modeling¶

initial state = Doctor in (0, 0) and Temple as it is in input

goal state = Doctor(s) in (n-1, m-1) and Temple with no potions

action = go up(x = x+1), go down(x = x-1), go right(y = y+1), go left(y = y-1) (if there is no obstacle(blocked cell or map boundries)

get potion(add it to list of tockens), get drug(new doctor in (0,0) and add drug to list of tockens)

BFS¶

in this algorithm when we select a state we will add the states we can go from it to them to the FIFO queue and we check if they are final state before adding them to the queue this algorithm is better than DFS time wise but memmory wise it is worse but it is opmimal and if there is a solution it will find it(completeness)

In [44]:
import collections
from collections import defaultdict

def searchBFS(t, initState):
    statesSeen = 0
    path = [(0,0)]
    q = collections.deque([path])
    n = len(t)
    m = len(t[0])
    dirc = [(1,0), (-1,0), (0,1), (0, -1)]
    queue = collections.deque([initState])
    while queue:
        state = queue.popleft()
        path = q.popleft()

        if state[0]:
            x, y = state[0].pop(0)
            statesSeen += 1
            for i, j in dirc:
                if 0<=x+i<n and 0<=y+j<m and t[x+i][y+j] <=0:
                    s = [[x for x in state[0]], state[1], [x for x in state[2]], state[3], [x for x in state[4]]]
                    s[3] += 1
                    if x+i == n-1 and y+j == m-1:
                        if len(state[0]) == 0 and len(state[2]) == state[1]:
                            path.append((x+i, y+j))
                            return path, statesSeen, s[3]
                    else:
                        s[0].append((x+i, y+j))
                        if t[x+i][y+j]==-1:
                            if (x+i, y+j) not in s[2]:
                                s[2].append((x+i, y+j))
                        elif t[x+i][y+j]==-2:
                            if (x+i, y+j) not in s[4]:
                                s[4].append((x+i, y+j))
                                s[0].append((n-1, 0))
                    path.append((x+i, y+j))
                    queue.append(s)
                    q.append(path.copy())
                    path.pop()
    return False

IDS¶

in this algorithm when we select a state we will add the states we can go from it to the LIFO queue and we check if they are final state before adding them to the queue and then we select top of the queue and do every thing all over again this algorithm is better than DFS time wise and better than both BFS and DFS memmory wise it is also opmimal and if there is a solution it will find it(complete)

In [115]:
def searchIDS(t, initState):
    maxDepth = 21
    statesSeen = 0
    n = len(t)
    m = len(t[0])
    dirc = [(1,0), (-1,0), (0,1), (0, -1)]
    for limit in range(1, maxDepth):
        queue = collections.deque([[[x for x in initState[0]], initState[1], [x for x in initState[2]], initState[3], [x for x in initState[4]]]])
        dq = collections.deque([0])
        path = [(0,0)]
        q = collections.deque([path])
        while queue:
            state = queue.pop()
            depth = dq.pop()
            path = q.pop()
            if depth <= limit:
                if state[0]:
                    x, y = state[0].pop(0)
                    statesSeen += 1
                    for i, j in dirc:
                        if 0<=x+i<n and 0<=y+j<m and t[x+i][y+j] <=0:
                            s = [[x for x in state[0]], state[1], [x for x in state[2]], state[3], [x for x in state[4]]]
                            s[3] += 1
                            if x+i == n-1 and y+j == m-1:
                                if len(state[0]) == 0 and len(state[2]) == state[1]:
                                    path.append((x+i, y+j))
                                    return path, statesSeen, s[3]
                            else:
                                s[0].append((x+i, y+j))
                                if t[x+i][y+j]==-1:
                                    if (x+i, y+j) not in s[2]:
                                        s[2].append((x+i, y+j))
                                elif t[x+i][y+j]==-2:
                                    if (x+i, y+j) not in s[4]:
                                        s[4].append((x+i, y+j))
                                        s[0].append((n-1, 0))               
                            path.append((x+i, y+j))
                            
                            queue.append(s)
                            dq.append(depth+1)
                            q.append(path.copy())
                            
                            path.pop()
    return False

A* search¶

Heuristic (h) = manhattan distance¶

in this algorithm when we select a state we will add the states we can go from it to a priority queue and we check if they are final state when selecting them from the queue and we select top of the queue witch is the state s that it's h(s) + g(s) is minimum and do every thing all over again this algorithm is better than DFS, BFS, IDS, ... both time and memmory wise it is also opmimal if the heuristic is consistant and if there is a solution it will find it(complete) we don't have a jump action or anything like it so if we want to go from state a to state b we should at least traverse the manhattan distance so it is consistant and we chose it as our heuristic

In [220]:
def h(loc, m, n):
    alfa = 1
    #alfa = 1.2
    #alfa = 5
    manhattanDistance = 0
    for x, y in loc:
        manhattanDistance += (n - 1 - x) + (m - 1 - y)
    return manhattanDistance*alfa

import heapq

def searchAstar(t, initState):
    n = len(t)
    m = len(t[0])
    
    statesSeen = 0
    stateList = [(h([(0,0)],m,n), initState, [(0,0)])]

    dirc = [(1,0), (-1,0), (0,1), (0, -1)]
    while stateList:
        heapq.heapify(stateList)
        curr = heapq.heappop(stateList)
        state = curr[1]
        path = curr[2]
        f = curr[0]
        
        if state[0]:
            x, y = state[0].pop(0)
            statesSeen += 1
            for i, j in dirc:
                if 0<=x+i<n and 0<=y+j<m and t[x+i][y+j] <=0:
                    s = [[x for x in state[0]], state[1], [x for x in state[2]], state[3], [x for x in state[4]]]
                    s[3] += 1
                    if x+i == n-1 and y+j == m-1:
                        if len(state[0]) == 0 and len(state[2]) == state[1]:
                            path.append((x+i, y+j))
                            return path, statesSeen, s[3]
                    else:
                        s[0].append((x+i, y+j))
                        if t[x+i][y+j]==-1:
                            if (x+i, y+j) not in s[2]:
                                s[2].append((x+i, y+j))
                        elif t[x+i][y+j]==-2:
                            if (x+i, y+j) not in s[4]:
                                s[4].append((x+i, y+j))
                                s[0].append((n-1, 0))
                    path.append((x+i, y+j))
                    
                    child = (s[3]+h(s[0],m,n), [[x for x in s[0]], s[1], [x for x in s[2]], s[3], [x for x in s[4]]], path.copy())
                    heapq.heappush(stateList, child)
                    
                    path.pop()
    return False
